{{about|the sign|other uses|Beware of the Dog (disambiguation)}} [[File:Cave canem MAN Napoli Inv110666.jpg|thumb|Mosaic at [[Pompeii]]]] [[File:Dom dramaturga.jpg|thumb|The ''Cave canem'' [[Roman mosaic]] at the entrance to the [[House of the Tragic Poet]] in [[Pompeii]], Italy, 2nd century BC]] [[File:Bewareofdog.JPG|thumb|Notice at the [[Glasgow Necropolis]]]]
'''Beware of the dog''' (also rendered as '''Beware of dog''') is a [[warning sign]] indicating that a dangerous dog is within. Such signs may be placed to deter [[burglary]] even if there is no dog.<ref>{{citation|title=How young house burglars choose targets|author=R Wright, RH Logie|journal=The Howard Journal of Criminal Justice|year=1988}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Deconstructing the fort|author=C Wilkinson|journal=Journal of Australian Studies|year=1998}}</ref>
==History== Warning signs of this sort have been found in [[Ancient Rome|ancient Roman]] buildings such as the [[House of the Tragic Poet]] in [[Pompeii]], which contains a [[mosaic]] with the caption ''[[cave canem]]'' ({{IPA-la|ˈka.weː ˈka.nẽ|pron}}). Some suppose that these warnings may sometimes have been intended to prevent visitors from stepping upon small, delicate dogs of the [[Italian Greyhound]] type.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4OI6G9fCwlwC&pg=PR7|pages=10–11|year=2004|title=The Rosetta bone|isbn=978-0-7645-4421-7|author=Cheryl S. Smith}}</ref>
==Law== Under [[English law]], placing such a sign does not relieve the owner of responsibility for any harm which may come to people attacked by the dog.<ref>{{citation|title=Commentaries on the Liberty of the Subject and the Laws of England|author=James Paterson|year=1877|page=271}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=A treatise on the law of torts|page=285|author=[[Charles G. Addison]], [[Horace Gray Wood]]|year=1876}}</ref>
